english:
  title: A Record of Cheonggwan Mountain
  author: Seok Cheon-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The vital breath that flows through heaven and earth becomes rivers and streams when dispersed, and gathers into mountains and peaks when condensed. In the southern reaches of the Noryeong ridge, along the coast in the ancient lands of O-a County, stands Cheonggwan Mountain. Its tail curls into desolate corners while its head dissolves into the vast ocean, rising and falling in towering majesty across territories spanning several provinces—surely this is where great vital breath accumulates in abundance.

    Tradition holds that this mountain is also called Jijei Mountain, and as the Flower Garland Sutra teaches, there exists a place called Jijei Mountain where bodhisattvas dwell. The present bodhisattva known as Cheonggwan is none other than this. On the southern slope of the mountain stand stacked stones standing many fathoms high—these are one of the eighty-four thousand stupas that King Ashoka of the Western Regions erected through the miraculous power of the Holy Teacher. Above the precipice before this stupa rises a tiered platform, roughly a fathom high, where our Buddha and Kashyapa once sat in peaceful repose. According to the Record of Buddha's Vows, my Lord declared: "In the place where I and Kashyapa sit in repose, Ashoka shall erect a stupa for my veneration after my parinirvana." Surely this is that very place.

    During the reign of King Hyocho of Silla, when the Reverend Busseok dwelt beneath this mountain, he established what is now known as Uisang Hermitage. The site commands the critical strategic position, and its crystalline beauty stands unrivaled beneath heaven. Opening one's window and gazing downward, all the myriad charms of lake and mountain pour into one's leisurely seat, stilling the heart and loosening the form until one enters the profound realms of wisdom. Thus we know that our Buddha and Kashyapa did indeed sit in repose here—no mere fable, this.

    Later, the Venerable Tongryeong founded a temple to the east of the stupa, now called Tapsan Temple. This master once dreamed that a northern promontory emerged from the earth, and his staff flew over the mountaintop to plant itself there. Upon that shadowy spot where the staff was fixed, he cleared the thorns and vines to build a monastery, which we now call Cheonggwan Temple.

    When Silla's King Sinho served as crown prince, he suffered royal rebuke and was exiled to Wando in the southern mountains. The great master Hwaeom Hongzhen, being intimate with the prince, heard of the urgent danger to the Eastern Palace and rushed to take refuge in this temple. Day and night he performed reverent obeisance, chanting the Flower Garland Sutra and invoking the celestial multitude. The heavenly hosts, moved by his devotion, responded to his call and assembled in rows upon the southern peak of the temple, which is now known as the Rock of Celestial Multitudes.

    Gazing from the temple's southern reaches, the rock formations grow ever more wondrous: the sharply towering Stone is called the Banner Rock; the precipitously jutting Stone is the Drum Rock; the bent and deferential Stone is the Bowing Rock; the crouching Stone resembles a lion displaying its mane and is called the Lion Rock; the tiered accumulations resemble stacked offerings and are known as the Upper and Lower Storehouse Rocks; the majestic central Stone stands alone in honor and is called the Vairocana Rock; while the peaked formations flanking both sides to fill the gaps are named the Manjushri and Samantabhadra Rocks.

    Indeed, in places where the great practitioners of the Flower Garland teaching walked their path, the realms of form and mind shine forth mutually, and subject and object become one truth. Thus the naming of these stones by what they resemble is no mere fanciful exercise.

    From Cheonggwan Temple, ascending southward five hundred paces, a small hermitage nestles beneath cliff-faces, drawing in the essence of nine rocks, and is thus named the Hermitage of Nine Essences. Should one dwell here whose heart is not pure, the spirits will surely terrify them, rendering residence impossible. But should one's mind be genuinely purified, they will surely feel stars and moon enter their breast, and hear golden bells resound through stone valleys. All who cultivate meditation and wisdom-study shall surely fulfill their vows. Thus the master Beop-ryang of Namak once came to reside here, first hearing bell-tones, then witnessing starlight, and by the twenty-first day attaining the dharani, earning praise as supreme in wisdom-understanding.

    Climbing upward one hundred paces from the hermitage's entrance along the cliff face, one reaches a broad stone platform called the Platform of Joy, for those struggling through dangerous terrain find gladness upon resting here. Beyond this platform, through tangled forest, an ancient path has worn into a trail. Following this path upward to the mountain's crown, the vista opens boundlessly. Clouds and sunset shimmer with clarity, grasses and trees glow with brilliance, and the remnants of mountains and waters stretch like coiled emerald snails and white silk across one's palm.

    Descending south from the summit about thirty li brings one to Seon-am Temple. The clustered rocks to the temple's north are where earthly immortals dwelled, surely kindred to such masters as the Cinnabar Cliff Sage and the Yellow Stone Lord. North of the Amitabha Hermitage upon a distant peak stands a spiritual stone, some eight feet in height, which responds with movement when one pushes it—how remarkable! Nearby lies the Bulrush Rock with its squared well of but a foot's depth, wherein clear spring water bubbles eternally unfailing through the seasons, and green bulrush stalks grow from stone crevices as if some guardian spirit tends them.

    Beyond these, the landscape sprawls in such strange and peculiar formations—sharp, flat, hollowed, gaping, soaring, and sunken shapes clustered together in infinite configurations and wonder—that one cannot exhaust recording them all. Has not the Creator concentrated sublime essence within this place and bound it with the great ocean as its limit?

    Alas, the ancients held a passion for mountains and waters. Some wore waxed wooden shoes to climb them, others rode their donkeys backward in descent, some lingered for nights forgetting to return, others departed never to come back. Yet their devotion was not merely to feast their eyes upon towering peaks or their ears upon babbling streams and thereby please their emotions. Rather, they fixed their hearts between mountain and water, pursuing the joy that such realms afford, seeking to recover their original nature and attain the Way.

    Moreover, for great bodhisattvas whose vision encompasses all, the splendor of the Flower Garland cosmos manifests right before them, and the countless friends in the Hundred Cities lie within reach of a half-step. Thus even should the Creative Force contract and expand, swallowing and regurgitating mountains and seas, these remain mere secondary matters—nothing worthy of wonder.

    In the autumn seventh month of the year Kyeongja, I once wandered these mountains seeking out sacred traces. Damjo, the master of Tapsan, showed me an ancient record and said: "This manuscript lay scattered in the dwellings behind the mountain. By chance I recovered it, but time has worn it into tatters with much text effaced. Should we decipher its meaning anew and present it to future generations, surely this becomes a thread in the transmission of the dharma." At that moment I was myself called to other duties and had no leisure to devote thought to it. Later, one named Damil also presented me with this same manuscript, which I kept folded in a box for quite some time. Only recently, on a spare day, did I chance to examine it again. I have thus roughly recorded its essential outlines to fulfill his intention, and hereby return both the manuscript and this account.
  footnotes:
    - 'Ashoka: The great Indian Buddhist emperor (circa 268-232 BCE) who erected 84,000 stupas throughout his kingdom to house relics of the Buddha.'
    - 'Jijei Mountain: In Buddhist cosmology, a sacred mountain where bodhisattvas reside, referenced in the Flower Garland Sutra (Avatamsaka Sutra).'
    - 'Kashyapa: One of the Buddha''s principal disciples, often depicted as his attendant and successor.'
    - 'Flower Garland Sutra: The Avatamsaka Sutra, a foundational Mahayana Buddhist text emphasizing the interconnectedness of all phenomena.'
    - 'The ''Hundred Cities'': A reference to the pilgrimage narrative in the Flower Garland Sutra where Sudhana visits countless spiritual teachers.'
    - 'Dharani: A sacred formula or incantation believed to contain concentrated spiritual power.'
